discription: Indicates that the actor has closed the object. For instance
column3: the object could represent a ticket being tracked in an issue management system.

discription: Indicates that the actor has deleted the object. This implies
column4: the permanent destruction of the object.

discription: Indicates that the actor has opened the object. For instance
column3: the object could represent a ticket being tracked in an issue management system.

discription: Indicates that the actor has read the object.
Indicates the actor replied to a question
column3: where the object is generally an activity representing the question. The text of the answer will often be included in the response inside result.

discription: Indicates the actor made an effort to access the object. An attempt statement without additional activities could be considered incomplete in some cases.
Indicates the actor finished or concluded the activity normally.
Indicates the activity provider has determined that the actor successfully started an activity.
Indicates the actor engaged with a physical or virtual object.
Indicates the actor attempted to start an activity.
Indicates a value of how much of an actor has advanced or moved through an activity.
Used to indicate a user responding to a help or chat request
Indicates the actor's intent to openly provide access to an object of common interest to other actors or groups.
Indicates that the actor successfully ended an activity.
The actor posted a reply to a forum
Indicates that the actor has viewed the object.
Indicates that the actor has voted up for a specific object. This is analogous to giving a thumbs up.
Persisting the current location (page) where the reader stopped the ebook activity.
Add annotation or notes to selected text within an ebook or highlight.
Indicates the activity provider has determined that the session was abnormally terminated either by an actor or due to a system failure.
Indicates the actor has created an object.
Indicates that the learning activity requirements were met by means other than completing the activity. A waived statement is used to indicate that the activity may be skipped by the actor.
